   <note type="biographical/historical" displayLabel="Biographical Note">Mississippi planter William Bisland purchased land on Bayou Terrebonne, 12 miles south of Houma, Louisiana in 1828. Originally named Richland Plantation, portions of the property were renamed Hope Farm and Aragon. Bisland properties in Terrebonne Parish consisted of several sugarcane plantations.  Following their fatherâ€™s death, Hope Farm and Aragon were purchased by William Alexander Bisland and John Rucker Bisland in 1853. Their brother, Thomas Shields Bisland, moved to Hope Farm following the Civil War. Subsequent owners of Hope Farm Plantation include James Bradford in 1887, and the Ellender Brothers of Hardscrabble, 1889-1924.</note>
